    "source": "396118758-Understanding-Wines-Explaining-Style-and-Quality.pdf_page_61",
    "contenu": "Certainly! Below is the structured data from the document image focusing on \"UNDERSTANDING WINES: EXPLAINING STYLE AND QUALITY.\"\n\n---\n\n**Title: UNDERSTANDING WINES: EXPLAINING STYLE AND QUALITY**\n\n### Microbiological Stability\n- Different forms of yeast and bacteria can spoil wine and make it completely undrinkable and unfit for sale.\n- It is important to keep winery equipment completely clean to avoid any risk from microbiological contamination.\n- Wines that are fortified because the high level of alcohol they contain is toxic for all microorganisms. However, a dry, high acid wine that has undergone MLF is naturally quite resistant to microbiological spoilage.\n- The yeast activity and the lack of nutrients mean that most alcohol or bacteria struggle to survive in wine.\n- This factor makes this type of bacteria, but some winemakers prefer to take this risk rather than sterile filter their wine, as described on page 51.\n- Wines that have not undergone MLF, as well as wines that have low to medium alcohol, low acidity and little residual sugar, are particularly at risk from yeast or bacterial spoilage.\n- Consequently, very careful handling and an appropriate amount of SO₂ is required to keep these protected at all times. They are also sterile filtered prior to packaging.\n\n### Oxygen Stability\n- Excessive levels of oxygen dissolved in the wine can cause it to degrade.\n- Overexposure to oxygen risks losing fresh fruit aromas and gradually turning brown.\n- The risk of oxidation can be minimized by avoiding exposure to oxygen and keeping SO₂ levels topped up.\n- Winemakers must take extra precautions during packaging to ensure that oxygen does not come into contact with the wine.\n- For example, bottles can be flushed with either carbon dioxide or nitrogen before filling to eliminate oxygen.\n\n### PACKAGING\n#### Packaging Alternatives\n- The majority of wine worldwide is packaged in glass bottles.\n- Alternative packaging options, like Tetra Paks and plastic bottles, are portable, cheap, and easy to handle.\n- They do not allow air to get into the wine, and importantly, they do not allow flavors to change.\n- Consumers generally prefer glass packaging due to its traditional association with wine.\n- Glass is heavier and adds transport costs, and its rigidity prevents it from being made to better protect the wine from oxygen exposure, unlike some newer packaging materials.\n\n### Image Analysis\n- Image showing a line up of different packaging options: bottle sizes from left to right; glass bottles, a bag-in-box, and two sizes of glass bottles.\n- Labels are visible on each packaging type demonstrating various branding and marketing approaches for wines:\n  * La Vilagerie - Vira Lomo, The Vin Rouge\n  * Australian Red Wine, Red Wine\n  * Grand Vin de Contract - Château Latrin\n\n---"
