    "contenu": "The document is a detailed exposition on various types of Port wine, which is a traditional Portuguese fortified wine. Below is the structured content detailing key points as explained in the document:\n\n---\n\n### True Tawny Ports\n- Undergo long oxidative maturation in barrels.\n- Made in a similar fashion regardless of style.\n- Exhibit flavors including dry fruits, walnuts, coffee, chocolate, and caramel.\n- Require little extra treatment during wood ageing.\n- Fully developed on release and do not need additional bottling preparation.\n- Majority are vintage styles, engaging continuously in blending and maturation processes.\n\n### Types of Port\n\n#### Ruby\n- Blends of wines aged between one and three years.\n- Lack much concentration.\n- Display primary flavors more typical of ruby styles.\n\n#### Tawny\n- Show a browning in color but are no older than common Ruby styles.\n\n### Ruby Ports\n- Have not undergone a long period of oxidative aging.\n- Possess options for lighter color through methods like blending with White Port or using less durão.\n- Applicable in regions such as the Baixo Corgo.\n\n### Special Categories of Port\n\n#### Reserve/Reserva\n- Labeling term for high-quality Tawny and Ruby Ports.\n- Determination of quality and classification by official tasting panels.\n- Requires a minimum of six years of aging.\n\n#### Late Bottled Vintage (LBV)\n- Aged between four and six years.\n- Typically undergoes extended aging in large oak vessels.\n- Mostly filtered and fined before release, causing them to be ready for drinking upon purchase.\n- A smaller number remain unfiltered.\n- These can benefit from bottle aging similar to vintage port.\n\n### General Notes\n- Detailed insights are given on handling and maturing of Port wines, highlighting different techniques and the effects on the taste and quality.\n- Blending and maturation is a continuous process, especially for vintage styles and reserves.\n- Additional care in bottling and release processes ensures the richness and quality standard of Port wines.\n\n----\n\nThis structured summary outlines fundamental knowledge about Port wine types, aging processes, and categorization. Each category and type of Port is explained with reference to maturation methods, aging requirements, and wine characteristics distinctive to their specific types."
