    "source": "inconnu_583",
    "contenu": "# Analysis of Document Content\n\n## Topic: Tokaji Aszú Wine\n\n### Sweetness Classification\nTokaji Aszú wines, originating from the region near the village of Gönc (famed for its barrel makers), classify their sweetness by a traditional measure called \"puttonyos.\" The number of puttonyos indicates the amount of aszú paste (a sweet, concentrated grape paste from botrytized grapes) added to the base wine. Here are some examples provided for understanding the classification:\n- Tokaji Aszú 2 Puttonyos contains 40 liters of aszú paste and 100 liters of base wine.\n- Tokaji Aszú 4 Puttonyos contains 80 liters of aszú paste and 60 liters of base wine.\n- The higher the puttonyos number, the sweeter and more concentrated the wine.\n- The sweetest category mentioned is 6 puttonyos.\n\n### Current Standards\nToday, classification by puttonyos is based on residual sugar content, following modern practices of using stainless-steel tanks rather than barrels for aging.\n\n### Production Details\nAszú paste is blended with base wine and can steep for as brief as eight hours or up to three days. The mixture is then drawn off and allowed to ferment in Tokaj’s distinctively small, cold, and often moldy cellars, which historically served as hiding spots during Turkish invasions. This second fermentation process can take anywhere from months to years due to the cold temperatures and high sugar content which slow fermentation significantly.\n\n### Aging Requirements\nUnder current regulations, Tokaji Aszú must age for a minimum of three years (in oak barrels and bottles), with typical bottles being 500-milliliter, smaller than standard wine bottles.\n\n### Historical Note\nTraditionally, as Tokaji wines aged, barrels were not topped up, creating airspace that, coupled with a unique strain of natural yeasts thriving in Tokaj’s cool dark cellars, would coat the wine's surface with a protective film.\n\n### Notable Vineyards\nThe Super First Class Mézes Mály vineyard is highlighted as one of the most renowned vineyards in the Tokaj region, emphasizing its prestige and significance in the Tokaji wine culture.\n\nThis document provides a comprehensive understanding of Tokaji Aszú wine, detailing its production methods, aging requirements, and historical significance in the wine industry."
