    "contenu": "The document appears to be from a book, specifically from a page labeled \"THE VINE\" on page 21. It discusses aspects of vine growth, structure, and pruning. Below is the structured content derived from the document text:\n\n---\n\n**One-year-old Wood**\n- Shoots turn woody during the winter after they have grown. The following spring, they become one-year-old wood, and the buds that formed on them the previous year burst and grow into shoots. Managing the one-year-old wood is vital for the grape grower because vines will normally only produce fruit on shoots that grow from buds that developed the previous year. Every winter the vine is pruned and the one-year-old wood will either be called a cane or a spur depending on how many buds it is left with. A cane is long, with eight to 20 buds, whereas a spur is short and has only two to three buds. This is discussed further in the section *Vine Pruning* in Chapter 6.\n\n**Permanent Wood**\n- This is wood that is more than one-year-old. In the vineyard the amount of permanent wood is restricted by pruning. The permanent wood is made up of the trunk and, where present, the arms of the vine. Not every vine has the same configuration of permanent wood. This is further discussed in the section *Vine Training* in Chapter 6.\n\n**The Roots**\n- The function is to absorb water and nutrients from the soil, anchor the vine and store carbohydrates to allow the vine to survive the winter. In modern vineyards most *V. vinifera* are grafted onto root systems from other species because they cannot resist *Phylloxera*. See section *Phylloxera and Rootstocks* on page 22.\n\n**Images and Captions in the Document:**\n1. Upper right image: A spur-pruned vine in Spain. Labels: one-year-old wood: spur, permanent wood: trunk.\n2. Middle right image: A cane-pruned vine in Alsace, France. Labels: one-year-old wood: cane, permanent wood: trunk.\n3. Lower right image: A spur-pruned vine in Australia. Labels: one-year-old wood: spur, permanent wood: arm (cordon), trunk.\n\nThis page mainly serves as an informational guide on the biology of vines, specifically focusing on the growth cycle of one-year-old wood and the management of permanent structures of the vine, as well as providing information about the vine's root system and its importance for survival and productivity."
